ion></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algebra" title=3D"Algebra">a=
lgebra</a>, <b>synthetic division</b> is a method for manually performing <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_division_of_polynomials" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Euclidean division of polynomials">Euclidean=
 division of polynomials</a>, with less writing and fewer calculations than=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_long_division" title=
=3D"Polynomial long division">long division</a>.
</p><p>It is mostly taught for division by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Linear" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear">linear</a> <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monic_polynomial" title=3D"Monic polynomi=
al">monic polynomials</a> (known as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Ruffini%27s_rule" title=3D"Ruffini's rule">Ruffini's rule</a>), but the m=
ethod can be generalized to division by any <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Polynomial" title=3D"Polynomial">polynomial</a>.
</p><p>The advantages of synthetic division are that it allows one to calcu=
late without writing variables, it uses few calculations, and it takes sign=
ificantly less space on paper than long division. Also, the subtractions in=
 long division are converted to additions by switching the signs at the ver=
y beginning, helping to prevent sign errors.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Regular_synthetic_division"=
>Regular synthetic division</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/i=
ndex.php?title=3DSynthetic_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" titl=
e=3D"Edit section: Regular synthetic division"><span>edit</span></a><span c=
lass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The first example is synthetic division with only a <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monic_polynomial" title=3D"Monic polynomial">monic</a>=
 linear denominator <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline=
"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"disp=
lay: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{=
\displaystyle x-a}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
