<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Evaluating_polynomials_by_t=
he_remainder_theorem">Evaluating polynomials by the remainder theorem</h3><=
span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</spa=
n><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSynthetic_divisio=
n&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Evaluating poly=
nomials by the remainder theorem"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The above form of synthetic division is useful in the context of the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Polynomial_remainder_theorem" title=
=3D"Polynomial remainder theorem">polynomial remainder theorem</a> for eval=
uating <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univariate" title=3D"Univar=
iate">univariate</a> polynomials. To summarize, the value of <span class=3D=
"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-i=
nline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://=
www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle p(x)}">
