<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Python_implementation">Pyth=
on implementation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
tle=3DSynthetic_division&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit s=
ection: Python implementation"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-edits=
ection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The following snippet implements Expanded Synthetic Division in <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Python_(programming_language)" title=3D"P=
ython (programming language)">Python</a> for arbitrary univariate polynomia=
ls:
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-highlight mw-highlight-lang-python mw-content-ltr" dir=3D"=
ltr"><pre><span></span><span class=3D"k">def</span><span class=3D"w"> </spa=
n><span class=3D"nf">expanded_synthetic_division</span><span class=3D"p">(<=
/span><span class=3D"n">dividend</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"n">divisor</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
<span class=3D"w">    </span><span class=3D"sd">"""Fast polynomial division=
 by using Expanded Synthetic Division. </span>
<span class=3D"sd">    Also works with non-monic polynomials.</span>

<span class=3D"sd">    Dividend and divisor are both polynomials, which are=
 here simply lists of coefficients. </span>
<span class=3D"sd">    E.g.: x**2 + 3*x + 5 will be represented as [1, 3, 5=
]</span>
<span class=3D"sd">    """</span>
    <span class=3D"n">out</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span class=
=3D"nb">list</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">dividend</sp=
an><span class=3D"p">)</span>  <span class=3D"c1"># Copy the dividend</span=
>
    <span class=3D"n">normalizer</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span =
class=3D"n">divisor</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"mi">0</s=
pan><span class=3D"p">]</span>
    <span class=3D"k">for</span> <span class=3D"n">i</span> <span class=3D"=
ow">in</span> <span class=3D"nb">range</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><spa=
n class=3D"nb">len</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">divide=
nd</span><span class=3D"p">)</span> <span class=3D"o">-</span> <span class=
=3D"nb">len</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">divisor</span=
><span class=3D"p">)</span> <span class=3D"o">+</span> <span class=3D"mi">1=
</span><span class=3D"p">):</span>
        <span class=3D"c1"># For general polynomial division (when polynomi=
als are non-monic),</span>
        <span class=3D"c1"># we need to normalize by dividing the coefficie=
nt with the divisor's first coefficient</span>
        <span class=3D"n">out</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=
=3D"n">i</span><span class=3D"p">]</span> <span class=3D"o">/=3D</span> <sp=
an class=3D"n">normalizer</span>

        <span class=3D"n">coef</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span cl=
ass=3D"n">out</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"n">i</span><sp=
an class=3D"p">]</span>
        <span class=3D"k">if</span> <span class=3D"n">coef</span> <span cla=
ss=3D"o">!=3D</span> <span class=3D"mi">0</span><span class=3D"p">:</span> =
 <span class=3D"c1"># Useless to multiply if coef is 0</span>
            <span class=3D"c1"># In synthetic division, we always skip the =
first coefficient of the divisor,</span>
            <span class=3D"c1"># because it is only used to normalize the d=
ividend coefficients</span>
            <span class=3D"k">for</span> <span class=3D"n">j</span> <span c=
lass=3D"ow">in</span> <span class=3D"nb">range</span><span class=3D"p">(</s=
pan><span class=3D"mi">1</span><span class=3D"p">,</span> <span class=3D"nb=
">len</span><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">divisor</span><span=
 class=3D"p">)):</span>
                <span class=3D"n">out</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span=
 class=3D"n">i</span> <span class=3D"o">+</span> <span class=3D"n">j</span>=
<span class=3D"p">]</span> <span class=3D"o">+=3D</span> <span class=3D"o">=
-</span><span class=3D"n">divisor</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span cla=
ss=3D"n">j</span><span class=3D"p">]</span> <span class=3D"o">*</span> <spa=
n class=3D"n">coef</span>

    <span class=3D"c1"># The resulting out contains both the quotient and t=
he remainder,</span>
    <span class=3D"c1"># the remainder being the size of the divisor (the r=
emainder</span>
    <span class=3D"c1"># has necessarily the same degree as the divisor sin=
ce it is</span>
    <span class=3D"c1"># what we couldn't divide from the dividend), so we =
compute the index</span>
    <span class=3D"c1"># where this separation is, and return the quotient =
and remainder.</span>
    <span class=3D"n">separator</span> <span class=3D"o">=3D</span> <span c=
lass=3D"mi">1</span> <span class=3D"o">-</span> <span class=3D"nb">len</spa=
n><span class=3D"p">(</span><span class=3D"n">divisor</span><span class=3D"=
p">)</span>
    <span class=3D"k">return</span> <span class=3D"n">out</span><span class=
=3D"p">[:</span><span class=3D"n">separator</span><span class=3D"p">],</spa=
n> <span class=3D"n">out</span><span class=3D"p">[</span><span class=3D"n">=
separator</span><span class=3D"p">:]</span>  <span class=3D"c1"># Return qu=
otient, remainder.</span>
</pre></div>
